City of Markham Land Acknowledgement 
We begin today by acknowledging the traditional territories of Indigenous peoples and their 
commitment to stewardship of the land. We acknowledge the communities in circle. The North, West, 
South and Eastern directions, and Haudenosaunee, Huron- Wendat, Anishnabeg, Seneca, Chippewa, 
and the Mississaugas of the Credit peoples. We share the responsibility with the caretakers of this land 
to ensure the dish is never empty and to restore relationships that are based on peace, friendship, and 
trust. We are committed to reconciliation, partnership and enhanced understanding.
Our Mission Statement
Working with the community to provide high-quality municipal services that meet, if not exceed, the 
expectations of residents and businesses. 
Our Vision
Markham, the leading Canadian municipality – embracing technological innovation, celebrating 
diversity, characterized by vibrant and healthy communities – preserving th

mmunity ..........................................................................44

Page  4
Welcome to the City of Markham! Whether you’re just moving in, or have 
been part of our community for years, we’re thrilled you chose our city. At 
the City of Markham, we are committed to providing you with excellent 
services by excellent people. This is our excellence journey and we want 
to exceed your expectations.
I’m pleased to present you with the Good Neighbour Handbook. Please 
use this resource as a guide to familiarize yourself with Markham, find out 
how to stay connected with us, and find information and tips on how to 
be a good neighbour.
To ensure you’re fully informed and connected with everything our city 
has to offer, we encourage you to visit our website (markham.ca).
Whether you’re curious about upcoming City projects, or simply want to 
explore what our community has to

offer, our website is your one-stop 
destination for all things related to city living. We’re committed to serving 
you and making your experience in our community a positive one.
Please take the time to review this handbook so you can be a good 
neighbour to others. As always, we’re here to support you every step of 
the way as you settle into life in our vibrant and diverse community.
Message from the Mayor
Mayor Frank Scarpitti

Birthplace: Milliken Mills Park
Favourite Things: Interacting with 
residents and smelling flowers in Markham’s 
pollinator gardens.
Known for: Canada’s first municipal 
mascot and champion of City of Markham 
programs and services.
Mission: Bringing people toge

ther and 
representing the values of hope, inclusivity 
and acceptance. Much like Millie’s 
hometown of Markham, Ontario, butterflies 
are known for transformation, creativity and 
infinite potential. Millie captures the hearts 
of all with mesmerizing wings adorned in a 
kaleidoscope of hues.
Millie
Markham Millie
There once was a caterpillar called Millie.
She lived in a town that became a city.
In her home of leaves and trees
she chewed as she pleased,
getting ready for her transformation.
Soon it was time to hang upside down,
so she said goodbye to her little town.
When she awoke, she fluttered and flew,
saw the comforting old and exciting new
of her home in the City of Markham.
After her happy life as a caterpillar ended,
a new one began, even more splendid!
Page  7

Page  8
Access Markham Mobile App 
The official City of Markham mobile app, provides 
access to information about programs and 
services – anywhere, anytime.
Use it to find information on:
•Recycling and garbage colle

ction schedule
with personalized notifications
•What Goes Where search tool to help you
dispose of items correctly
•Bikeways, parks and paths
•Report a problem
•Winter maintenance
The app is available on:
MappiT 
MappiT is the City of Markham’s 
Development Application Viewer. 
Members of the public can look 
up various development applications and tree 
removal permits to check on their status.  
Try it out: markham.ca/MappIt
eNews - Markham Now 
Stay up-to-date on City news 
and events with Markham Now,  
delivered on a bi-weekly basis 
to your inbox. 
Sign up to receive this free eNewsletter at  
markham.ca/MarkhamNow, and if you 
know someone in Markham who would also 
enjoy receiving this news, please encourage 
them to sign up too.
City of Markham 
Virtual Assistant 
The City of Markham’s Artificial 
Intelligence (AI)-enabled Virtual 
Assistant provides users with 
24/7 access to a wide range of 
topics, anytime, anywhere and 
on any device. 
Questions you can ask the Assistant i

nclude: 
What events are happening in Markham? 
How do I register for a program?, as well as 
more than 100 additional City-related topics. 
Try it out at markham.ca    
Follow us on Social Media:
Stay Connected with Markham

Page  9
Operating construction equipment or noisily 
moving around containers and materials of 
any kind (except for moving your household 
belongings) are not permitted after 7 PM 
or on Sundays or statutory holidays (federal 
or province-wide holidays). Saturday-noise 
construction is allowed from 9 AM to 5 PM. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Bylaw
Fireworks
Permits are not required the day before Victoria 
Day and on Victoria Day, and the day before 
Canada Day and on Canada Day. You will need a 
permit to set off fireworks on all other days. 
Family fireworks may only be set off on private 
property and with the homeowner’s consent. 
Fireworks are not allowed on City property, 
including parks, fields and roads. 
Under the Provincial Offences Act, violators may 
be fi

ned up to $5,000. 
For more information and to apply for a permit, 
visit markham.ca/Fireworks
Noise and Public Disturbances 
General Noise Guide:
Guns, rifles, and toys that use a combustion 
engine are not allowed on city streets, and 
must never be used on your property or in 
your neighbourhood. These may include 
model airplanes and cars, track bikes, 
snowmobiles and other riding toys. Quiet, 
electric or battery-driven toys are allowed.
Playing amplified or loud music outdoors 
is permitted from 7 AM to 5 PM Monday 
to Thursday, and 7 AM to 11 PM Friday to 
Saturday, and 9 AM to 5 PM on Sunday.
Shouting, whistling and singing is not 
allowed after 11 PM.
Noise Exemption Permits are required for 
outdoor functions on private property after 
11 PM.
All other noises, such as honking  
horns and electronic sounds, are not 
permitted after 7 PM or on Sundays or 
statutory holidays (federal or province- 
wide holidays).
Good Neighbour Relations

Page  10
Smoking and Vaping Cannabis 
S

moking and vaporizing of recreational 
cannabis is prohibited in all public places  
in Markham.
Offenders may be subject to fines or penalties  
of up to $1,000. 
Medical cannabis use is exempt from our 
Cannabis By-Law and subject to relevant federal 
and provincial legislation.
Sharing Public Parks  
and Playgrounds 
City of Markham parks, trails and public spaces 
promote a safe, active and healthy outdoor 
experience for residents and visitors. 
The City of Markham and its residents take 
pride in Keeping Markham Beautiful and 
encourage all users of outdoor spaces to do 
their part. 
Learn more:  
markham.ca/KeepMarkhamBeautiful
Good Neighbour Relations

Page  11
Neighbourhood Watch
Neighbourhood Watch is supported by 
York Regional Police. It is important to 
help to reduce crime through the active 
participation of citizens in crime prevention. 
Work with your neighbours to prevent 
crime before it starts.  
Email NeighbourhoodWatch@yrp.ca for 
more information.
Short-Term Prop

erty 
Accommodations 
A short-term rental accommodation is a 
dwelling unit that is rented out for less than 
30 consecutive days. Short-term rental 
accommodations are commonly associated 
with application platforms like AirBnB or VRBO. 
Short-term rental accommodations are not 
permitted in the City. Anyone renting a unit 
for longer than 30 consecutive days would be 
subject to the Residential Tenancies Act, and 
would not be considered a short-term rental 
accommodation.
Good Neighbour Relations

Page  12
Rooming Houses
Generally speaking, a rooming house 
is a dwelling unit occupied by multiple 
individuals under separate tenancies, who do 
not function as a single housekeeping unit.  
Rooming houses are not permitted in the City. 
For more information, please contact the 
Development Services Commission at  
dsc@markham.ca
Additional Dwelling Units
Additional dwelling units (often called 
basement apartments, second suites, granny 
flats, coach houses, or garden homes) are now 
b

roadly permitted throughout the City, as long 
as certain development standards are met, 
such as required parking, and setbacks to any 
buildings or stairs. The creation of any new 
dwelling unit requires a building permit prior 
to the start of construction.  
Information on the building permit process 
and applicable zoning provisions can be found 
online at markham.ca/Building
Good Neighbour Relations

Page  13
Thinking of Renovating  
Your Home?
Make sure you understand zoning requirements 
and obtain any necessary building permits for 
work proposed on your property.
All construction must comply with the 
applicable zoning by-law for your property. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Building 
For building permit questions, contact 
buildingstandards@markham.ca  
or 905.475.4870.
Heritage Conservation Districts 
Make sure you obtain a Heritage Permit for any 
exterior alterations such as painting, and new or 
changes to pathways and driveways. 
For more information, email  
heritage@markham.

ca
Reduce Litter –  
Let’s All Do Our Part 
Did you know? Most litter comes from overfilled 
blue boxes. On windy days put your blue box 
out in the morning, not the night before. Don’t 
overload your blue box – keep the material  
below the rim. Don’t dump household garbage  
in parks or on trails. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Recycling
Property Care 
Keep your garden beds tidy by installing  
2 to 3 inches of wood chip mulch. 
Wood chip mulch helps suppress weeds, 
conserve moisture to help plants grow during 
the dry and hot Summer months, and provide 
nutrients as they decompose over time. 
Wood chips can also be added around the base 
of your tree for the same benefits. Make sure 
the wood chips are at least 5 inches away from 
the trunk of the tree.  
Learn about our Mulch Giveway at:  
markham.ca/KeepMarkhamBeautiful
Winter Season
In the Winter, remember to keep your home’s 
hot water and furnace exhaust pipes clear of 
snow and ice to avoid carbon monoxide build 
up, which can be de

adly.
If there is a snow-covered fire hydrant near 
your home, keep it clear for easy access and 
visibility in case of an emergency.
When you’re shovelling snow on your driveway 
or walkway, don’t shovel snow back onto the 
road. If you do, you will be subject to fines by 
Municipal by-laws and the Ontario Highway 
Traffic Act.
 Track our plows using the Winter Maintenance 
App at markham.ca/Winter
Maintaining Your Property

Page  14
Overgrown Vegetation 
The yard around every home must be kept 
neat and tidy, and free of garbage or anything 
that might cause a health or safety danger. 
The earth must be covered with either grass 
and plants or a covering that is designed to 
stop the soil from blowing or draining away.
Grass must be trimmed to grow no higher 
than 15 centimetres (6 inches).
Trees and bushes must also be kept  
trimmed and tidy. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Bylaw 
Downspout Disconnection 
Program
This program reduces the risk of basement 
flooding. It also limits environme

ntal concerns 
caused by directly connecting downspouts to 
the sanitary sewer system. 
These connections increase the flow of 
rainwater into the sanitary sewer system 
during heavy or long rain events.  
Learn more:  
markham.ca/DownspoutProgram
Winter Weather and  
Frozen Pipes Prevention 
Extreme Winter weather can lead to frozen pipes 
in your home.  When water freezes in a pipe, 
there is no space for the ice to expand, and may 
cause the pipe to burst with pressure. This can 
cause damage to your property, costly repairs 
and unnecessary water waste.
From the property line to your home, you 
are responsible for plumbing, repairs and 
replacements. Call a plumber for household 
plumbing issues.  
Learn more: markham.ca/FrozenPipes
Swimming Pool and  
Hot Tub Draining 
Protect the environment and our community! 
Pools, hot tubs, and spas should always be 
drained properly. 
Do not drain chlorinated water or salt water 
from your pool directly into a storm drain. This 
water can ho

ld substances that are harmful 
to our environment, pets and local wildlife. 
Instead, de-chlorinate your pool and drain onto 
a porous area, such as your lawn.
Maintaining Your Property

Page  15
Accessory Buildings 
A new shed, sauna or other accessory building 
does not require a building permit if it has a 
footprint (the space on the ground that the 
building will take up) less than 10 square 
metres (108 square feet). Anything larger 
requires a building permit.
Even though a permit may not be required, the 
construction must comply with the applicable 
zoning by-law for your property. Access 
the Property Details Search to confirm the 
applicable zoning by-law. 
Copies of the by-laws can be viewed at the 
Development Services Counter, located inside 
the Markham Civic Centre, or by submitting 
a Zoning Search Request online to obtain the 
zoning information for your property. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Building
Rats and Unwanted Critters 
Follow these guidelines to keep rats and 
o

ther unwanted critters away:
• Do not leave food outside, and do not 
place your garbage out early.
• Put outdoor garbage bags in metal 
garbage cans with securely fitted lids to 
stop critters from feeding on contents.
• Clean around the house – less clutter 
means fewer places to hide. Clean up 
pet food and bird seed debris.
• Keep gardens free from debris and keep 
clutter to a minimum.
• If you have a compost heap, don’t 
include organic food waste as that will 
attract rats and critters. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Wildlife
Maintaining Your Property

Page  16
Graffiti 
Please report unauthorized and 
offensive graffiti to the City for removal 
by filling out our online form at: 
markham.ca/OnlineRequest 
Caring for Trees and  
Tree Permits 
For trees on private property, property 
owners must apply for a permit before 
injuring or destroying any tree in Markham 
with a trunk diameter of 20 centimetres 
(about 8 inches) or more, measured at 1.37 
metres (about 54 inches) above the gro

und 
at the base of the tree.  
Learn more: markham.ca/Trees
Love Your Hydrant 
Love Your Hydrant is a public education 
program that began in 2013 as a joint 
initiative between the Waterworks and 
Fire Departments. The goal is to educate 
and inform residents about proper care of 
neighbourhood hydrants by keeping them 
clear of snow, shrubs, and debris. 
Please report unauthorized use (water 
theft), damaged or vandalized hydrants to 
CustomerService@markham.ca  
or 905.477.5530.
Maintaining Your Property

Page  17
Maintaining Your Property
City Boulevards
• There is to be no alteration to City 
boulevards without a permit
• As per the Road Occupancy 
By-law, you can not alter the City 
boulevard to widen the curb, 
expand driveway apron, pave 
around trees, streetlights and 
utility boxes. Any deviation from 
the by-law will result in charges to 
the homeowner and requirement 
of rectifying the site to the City’s 
standard, which will be made at 
the homeowner’s expense
• For drive

way expansion and 
allowable driveway width for your 
property, please refer to the City 
Zoning By-law for details
• If you have questions about 
driveway and curb modification, 
please email ROW@markham.ca
Caring for Public  
Street Trees
Did you know? It is illegal to remove 
public street trees and/or pave over public 
municipal boulevard spaces. 
Your front and side property line is 
marked on your Plan of Survey – this 
document is usually filed when you 
purchase your property. 
To avoid potential by-law infraction 
and penalties, consult with a qualified 
surveyor to precisely determine your 
property boundary.
If you are planning to extend your 
driveway to accommodate additional 
parking, contact  
CustomerService@markham.ca  
for more information.

• Install a sump pump – if you have a low-
lying basement, or high water table. Ensure 
a storm water sump pump drains at least 
one metre from your house foundation
Be Bird-Friendly
Since 2014, the City has helped reduce bird-
window collisions through retrofitting existing 
municipal buildings, incorporating bird-
friendly design measures in new

municipal 
buildings, and encouraging best practices in 
new private developments.
How can you help? As a homeowner or 
business owner, you can adopt bird-friendly 
design treatments to your existing home 
or business, to continue the City’s efforts of 
becoming a more bird-friendly city.
Learn more: markham.ca/Birds
Catch Basin Clearing 
Reduce the risk of flooding on your property: 
• Regularly clean out your eavestroughs. 
Disconnect and redirect your 
downspouts to an unpaved area at least 
one metre away from your foundation
• Keep storm drains clear of leaves  
and litter 
• Create a rain-friendly landscape by 
replacing asphalt and other hard 
surfaces with gardens and plants
• Maintain your basement windows and 
foundation and ensure that water drains 
away from your foundation
• Limit water use inside your home during 
rainstorms (for example, delay laundry, 
taking a shower, using the dishwasher)
Maintaining Your Property

Page  21
Dog Leashing and  
Off-Leash Parks 
The City

of Markham requires all dogs to be 
leashed at all times on public property or 
within City parks, unless in a designated off-
leash dog park. 
The City currently provides and maintains four 
permanent off-leash dog park areas, and are in 
the process of implementing an additional 8 
temporary locations.
Every person accessing the off-leash dog park 
areas with their dog must comply with the 
Animal Protection and Services By-Law  
2018-91, the Parks By-law and the Dog Owners 
Liability Act. 
Dog owners are responsible for cleaning up 
after their dogs in parks and all public spaces.  
Learn more: markham.ca/DogParks 
Pet Licensing 
It’s the law to license your pet and renew  
the licence annually. Licences expire on 
December 31 every year.
If your pet is lost or stolen, this is the fastest 
way to reunite them with you! 
A pet licence also qualifies your pet for a free 
ride home if found at large. 
Avoid a $430 fine, and make sure your pet is 
licensed today! 
Apply now: markham.ca

/License
Livestock 
Livestock, such as chickens, ducks, cows, pigs 
and sheep, can not be kept in residential areas. 
This ensures the safety of our residents and  
the animals.
For questions concerning livestock, contact 
Animal Services at 905.415.7531.
Animal Services

Page  22
Pet Waste 
Pet waste contains bacteria and does not 
belong in park waste bins or left on the 
ground. Please pick up after your pet and bring 
waste home and put it in your green bin. 
In Markham, you can use any plastic bag to 
scoop (e.g. a bread bag, and they do not have 
to be compostable). 
Wildlife in the City 
Wildlife is an important part of the City’s 
ecosystem. Animal services provides care for 
sick and injured wildlife. 
It’s against the law to feed wild animals.  
Avoid a $615 fine. 
Please report any animal-related concern to the 
Animal Services Department at 905.415.7531.
The City has a Coyote Response and 
Coexistence Strategy that assists with 
mitigating negative coyote encounters. 
Learn

more: markham.ca/Wildlife
Animal Services

Page  23
Refer to the Property Details Search to  
confirm the by-law that applies to your property. 
Copies of the by-laws can be viewed at the 
Development Services Counter, located inside 
the Markham Civic Centre, or by submitting 
a Zoning Search Request online to obtain the 
zoning information for your property. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Building
Building a Shed 
A building permit is not required if you are 
building a single-storey accessory building  
(no plumbing) that is less than 15 square metres 
in area.
Even though a permit may not be required, the 
construction must comply with the applicable 
zoning by-law for your property. 
Access the Property Details Search on 
markham.ca/Building to confirm the 
applicable zoning by-law.
Copies of the by-laws can be viewed at the 
Development Services Counter or submit a 
Zoning Search request online to obtain the 
zoning information for your property.
Building Permits 
Building permits are

required for new 
construction, additions, and renovations to an 
existing building. 
A permit may also be required if you are 
replacing, repairing and/or adding any 
mechanical or plumbing systems.
All construction must comply with the 
applicable zoning by-law for your property.  
Learn more: markham.ca/Building
For building permit questions, contact 
buildingstandards@markham.ca or 
905.475.4870. For building heritage questions, 
contact heritage@markham.ca 
Accessory Buildings
The City of Markham’s building standards 
ensure a high level of quality in the design and 
construction of all our buildings and structures. 
A new shed, sauna or other accessory building 
may require a building permit. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Building
All construction must comply with the 
applicable zoning by-law for your property. 
Permits

Page  24
survey to figure out your fence boundary; 
if you need to be more accurate, a qualified 
surveyor can tell you exactly where these 
boundaries are. 
As per R

oad Occupancy By-law 2018-109, your 
fence shall not encroach onto City property.
Road Occupancy Permit 
A permit is required for any activity that might 
block a public road allowance. 
As noted in by-law 2018-109, there are  
certain activities that will require a Road 
Occupancy Permit.
You are not allowed to lay any landscape

Sewer Backups and Flooding 
The City of Markham and property owners 
have a shared responsibility. Markham 
maintains the public portion of the 
underground pipes – spanning from the water 
main to the municipal property line. Property 
owners are

responsible for the plumbing 
system that runs from their property line to 
inside the home.
To learn more, visit Property Owner vs City 
Responsibility at markham.ca/Water 
Fats, oils and grease (F.O.G.)
Never pour fats, oils and grease (such as 
cooking oil, condiments or salad dressings) 
down the drain or toilet. F.O.G can clog your 
pipes and result in expensive sewer backups 
and flooding in your house or apartment. 
Dispose of F.O.G in your kitchen catcher or 
green bin.  
Learn more: markham.ca/FogClogs
Don’t Flush This Stuff 
Never use your toilet as a garbage bin. Flushing 
items such as baby wipes, kitty litter, floss, 
hair and female sanitary products can block 
your home’s plumbing system, resulting in 
expensive repairs.   
Learn more: markham.ca/WhatGoesWhere

Tap Water Quality
Markham provides high-quality drinking 
water to residents and businesses through 
the following process:
1. City of Toronto draws water from

Lake Ontario and cleans it in their 
treatment plant.
2. York Region purchases treated water 
from Toronto and then stores and sells 
it to the City of Markham.
3. Markham distributes the water to its 
residents and businesses using over 
1,000 kilometres of watermains. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Water
Wastewater Collection 
Wastewater is produced through daily 
activities such as cleaning laundry, washing 
dishes and flushing the toilet. After used 
water goes down the drain, it flows past your 
property line and enters into Markham’s 
sanitary sewer system where it’s collected and 
moved to a treatment facility. 
Learn more: markham.ca/Water

Stormwater Management
Heavy rainfall and melting snow can 
overwhelm sewer systems causing severe 
flooding in our community. 
To protect your property from damage, 
Markham’s Private Plumbing Protection 
Program can offer you financial support for 
installing a flood protection device in your 
home, such as a backwater valve. 
Learn more: markham.ca/5pProgram 
Stormwater Fee
Flood control improvements are funded 
through the Stormwater Fee that is charged to 
all property owners - both residential ($54 per 
residential pr

operty), and non-residential ($30 
per $100,000 of Current Value Assessment). 
This fee, combined with revenue from the 
Canada Gas Tax, helps fund current and future 
stormwater infrastructure improvement 
projects city-wide. The fee is applied to the 
final tax bill for each property owner  
in Markham.
Stormwater Ponds 
Stormwater ponds reduce the risk of 
flooding in urban areas and trap sediments 
and pollutants from entering our 
stormwater system. 
While they may appear as attractive bodies 
of water, often surrounded by parks and 
trails, avoid doing the following:
• Swimming, skating or fishing and
• Releasing pets like fish or turtles
Be cautious around ponds, especially after 
a rainstorm when water levels have risen.
